âœ… IS and IS NOT in MySQL
In MySQL, IS and IS NOT are used to compare NULL values because = and != do not work with NULL.

ğŸ”¹ IS NULL and IS NOT NULL
ğŸ“Œ Check for NULL values
SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department IS NULL;

ğŸ“Œ Check for NOT NULL values
SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department IS NOT NULL;

ğŸ”¹ Why Not Use = for NULL?
SELECT * FROM employees WHERE department = NULL;  -- âŒ Wrong

âœ… Always use IS NULL instead of = NULL because NULL is not comparable using =.


ğŸ”¹ IS TRUE, IS FALSE, IS UNKNOWN
ğŸ“Œ Example: Using IS TRUE

SELECT * FROM orders WHERE payment_completed IS TRUE;

âœ… Finds orders where payment_completed = 1.
ğŸ“Œ Example: Using IS FALSE
SELECT * FROM orders WHERE payment_completed IS FALSE;


âœ… Finds orders where payment_completed = 0.
ğŸ“Œ Example: Using IS UNKNOWN (For NULL Values)

SELECT * FROM orders WHERE discount IS UNKNOWN;
âœ… Same as IS NULL, checks if discount is NULL.


ğŸš€ Summary
âœ… Use IS NULL / IS NOT NULL instead of = NULL
âœ… Use IS TRUE / IS FALSE for boolean values
âœ… Avoid using = and != with NULL


